ISSUES: Noted contact between liners sensors and casing.
OMD pipes contact has to be rectified.
Exhaust waste gate valve missing local indication.
Air waste gate valve missing local indication.
Crankcase pressure at time of FAT noted not stable, to be confirmed during commissioning.
Rubber element (silent block) from E34 found correded and damaged. Additional protection to be agreed between STX and Wartsila in order to prevent same problem.
Fuel pum cylinder head flange protections noted on present engine, to be clarifid the purpuses and possible retrofit to E34.
Centrifugal oil filter supporting to be improved or to be changed the type of valve. Refer to E34 claim.

HP fuel pump visual internal inspection (either in DCT or at L'Orange) is required after FAT and relevant report to be submitted as soon as available. Inspection will be witnessed by yard and owner rappresentative.
Owner request is one for the first 12V and one for the first 16V in case of inspection at L'Orange; two in case of inspection in DCT. 
In case of further action needed after inspection, steps will be agreed betwen the part.

HP fuel pumps: as previously remark during FAT of F34 and commissioning of E34 issues,  problem is still under evaluation. In case of modification required on a.m. costructions, corrective action to be performed during commissioing of G34.
Fuel and Lube oil analysis before and after FAT to be done and report to be send at the yard before start the commissioning.
LT AMOT valve of lube oil cooler to be properly supported due to vibration and failure of E34.
Relative high exh. gas temperature noted comparated with previous engine (E34/F34). Full explanation is required and confirmation that with summer condition will not reach limit value.
Oil cooler basement vibration to be invetigated.see also claim about E34 failure of fixation stud.
Hot box doors covers, locking device to be improved due to failure on E34.
Splashguard of IN/OUT fuel pipes to be checked during commissioning and improvement of structure to be done due to the failure observed on E34 (claim cm223).
Injector pressure test on test bench to be done satisfactory.
Detected minor scratches on roller tappet: A4 (exh.), A6 (inlet), B5 (inlet). To be polished.
Exhaust gas carbon deposit on inlet valve seats. Wartsila have to clarify.
Few minor paint damages found on crankcase i.w.o. the camshaft chambers.
Found some rust on the HT water not used flange. To be polished.

ISSUES: Rubber element (silent block) from E34 found corroded and damaged. Additional protection to be agreed between STX and Wartsila in order to prevent same problem.
Fuel pump head protection cover noted on present engine, to be clarified the purposes and possible retrofit to E34.
Centrifugal oil filter handle to be improved or to be changed the type of valve. Refer to E34 claim.

HP fuel pump visual internal inspection (either in DCT or at L'Orange) is required after FAT and relevant report to be submitted as soon as available. Inspection will be witnessed by yard and owner representative.
Owner request is one for the first 12V and one for the first 16V in case of inspection at L'Orange; two in case of inspection in DCT. 
In case of further action needed after inspection, steps will be agreed between the part.

HP fuel pumps: as previously remark during FAT of F34 and commissioning of E34 issues,  problem is still under evaluation. In case of modification required on a.m. constructions, corrective action to be performed during commissioning of G34.
Fuel and Lube oil analysis before and after FAT to be done and report to be send at the yard before start the commissioning.
LT AMOT valve of lube oil cooler to be properly supported due to vibration and failure of E34.
Relative high exh. gas temperature noted compared with previous engine (E34/F34). Full explanation is required and confirmation that with summer condition will not reach limit value.

Oil cooler basement vibration to be  investigated. See also claim about E34 failure of fixation stud.
Check the quality of the L.O.C. bolts and the design lastest applicable standard. Also lube oil cooler vibration has to be checked. (E34 claim CM044A).
Hot box doors/covers, locking device to be improved due to failure on E34.
Splashguard of IN/OUT fuel pipes to be checked during commissioning and improvement of structure to be done due to the failure observed on E34 (claim cm223).
Wartsila have to provide value (design nominal value) for clean fuel leakage on HFO and LFO at 100%.
Main bearing and Big end bearings shells found in satisfactory condition. Big end bearing shells has to be replaced according the Wartsila instruction manual.

FARE IL BLU PRESSO IL FORNITORE - 
nota: per l'albero in questione non siamo stati contattati né venerdì 4 né sabato 5, perciò se non fosse venuto Vezzani sabato di sua spontanea volontà, avremmo dovuto attendere la vostra chiamata lunedì 7 primo turno.
in merito alla non conformità riscontrata, è stata gestita nelle tempistiche previste per casi del genere.  già al mattino (ore 7:45 / 8) si poteva iniziare.
una soluzione sarebbe quella di condividere la pianificazione degl'alberi con la qualità in modo da migliorare le tempistiche dei controlli.

DA MODIFICARLO,PER ORA USIAMO I VECCHI che invece hanno il mantello pieno.

ISSUES: alzando le testate(rigenerate o già usate) ci siamo accorti che sulla valvola di aspirazione passa la sonda di un decimo e mezzo,rugosità all'altezza dell'o-ring della camicia,i yoke di scarico toccano sulla valvola e su due teste mancana l'iniettore e la spada chiamato il collaudo (cociani,mahnic) da decisioni abbiamo preferito lasciarle a terra e aspettare domani le decisioni dopo il controllo del collaudo.

comunque le teste vengono ripulite dalla servigen per renderle più presentabili, tutti gli yoke vengono sondati e dove necessario viene smerigliato l'eccesso di fusione.

ISSUES: IL PPRECEDENTE PROBLEMA DELL'ACCOPPIAMENTO ALBERO INCASTELLATURA, RIGUARDANTE L'ASSENZA DI UN INVITO SU BANCHI E BLOCCO, È ANCORA PRESENTE. POSSIAMO PROCEDERE NOI A SMUSSARE IL TUTTO O DEVE ESSERE FATTO IN FASE DI PULIZIA OPPURE NON SI PUÒ FARE???

RIAPPOGGIATO IL MOTORE SULLE MOLLE, LIMATI TUTTI GLI SPIGOLI PIù I DANNI CAUSATI DAL GRIPPAGGIO DEI BANCHI IN ACCOPPIATA, RIPULITA L'INCASTELLATURA E I BANCHI,E AL SECONDO TENTATIVO, GRAZIE AGLI INVITI CREATI SU BANCHI E INCASTELLATURA, L'ACCOPPIATA è RIUSCITA. PERSA UN ORA IN PIù IN 3 PERSONE

ISSUES:
WIT to clarify the following alarms on LDU:
- Invalid ISO code (NA)
- CV 381 and CV 391, VIC control valve A and B bank (NA)
SOLUTIONS:
- The cause of “Invalid ISO code” has been found and will be solve updating all SW packages.
- The notification on LDU screen about CV381 and CV391 is not a mistake. (and cannot be removed) It is due to the fact that the VIC load reduction safety is quite complex and need the evaluation of a pre-condition. The technical explanation is the follow: The notification on LDU screen about CV381 / 391 is not a proper alarm. In order to implement the Load reduction High for CV381 / 391 two logical block have been implemented inside Software. The first logical block “Delayed VIC off ” detects when the VIC command is deactivated (with a delay of 9sec) The second block performs the real Load Reduction using the first block as input (see image). :
When the first logical block is set to “1”, on the LDU screen a notification is displayed even if No Action are performed.
InternalNotes: Da fornire risposta sugli allarmi e se non possono essere esclusi spiegare il perchè non possiamo
MeasureTaken:
- The cause of “Invalid ISO code” has been found and will be solve updating all SW packages. :
- The notification on LDU screen about CV381 and CV391 is not a mistake. (and cannot be removed) It is due to the fact that the VIC load reduction safety is quite complex and need the evaluation of a pre-condition. The technical explanation is the follow: The notification on LDU screen about CV381 / 391 is not a proper alarm. In order to implement the Load reduction High for CV381 / 391 two logical block have been implemented inside Software. The first logical block “Delayed VIC off ” detects when the VIC command is deactivated (with a delay of 9sec) The second block performs the real Load Reduction using the first block as input (see image).
When the first logical block is set to “1”, on the LDU screen a notification is displayed even if No Action are performed.

ISSUES: WIT to make an official statement regarding the Overspeed Trip occurred during the load transitory from 85% to 100%.
SOLUTIONS: The overspeed occurred during the passage between 85% to 100% load was due to the untightening of the fuel rack blocking screw, that went to touch the control shaft of the engine fuel rack and causing the impossibility of the Woodward governor to increase the speed (the signal of the Woodward was 100% without effect on speed). When the test engineer saw that the engine speed was decreasing reduced immediately the load but the governor signal was at max and the engine has gone to overspeed.
MeasureTaken: The overspeed occurred during the passage between 85% to 100% load was due to the untightening of the fuel rack blocking screw, that went to touch the control shaft of the engine fuel rack and causing the impossibility of the Woodward governor to increase the speed (the signal of the Woodward was 100% without effect on speed). When the test engineer saw that the engine speed was decreasing reduced immediately the load but the governor signal was at max and the engine has gone to overspeed.

ISSUES: Found small amount of mud on cylinder liner water spaces, WIT to investigate.
SOLUTIONS:
Wärtsilä confirms that the cleanliness condition of the cooling water system of the engine is satisfactory. 
The cleanliness level of cylinder unit A2 was somewhat poorer that usual due to a small amount of mud-like impurity found on the top of the cylinder liner; however, the condition is considered acceptable. 
In light of the additional inspections performed on others engines  as well as from the opening inspection after Factory Acceptance Test carried out on remaining engines of the same project Fincantieri 6275, which confirmed a satisfactory cleanliness level, Wärtsilä considers the minor impurity noticed in the top of cooling water space of cylinder liner A2 of the engine in object as an accidental event. 
As additional corrective action, cooling water filters of test cell TA3 were inspected and the cooling water charge was totally renewed. 
Before reassembling the relevant cylinder head, the top of cylinder liner A2 was manually cleaned by a cloth soaked with solvent. 
Wärtsilä confirms that the engine in subject can be used without any restriction for its safe and sound operation
MeasureTaken:
Wärtsilä confirms that the cleanliness condition of the cooling water system of the engine is satisfactory. 
The cleanliness level of cylinder unit A2 was somewhat poorer that usual due to a small amount of mud-like impurity found on the top of the cylinder liner; however, the condition is considered acceptable. 
In light of the additional inspections performed on others engines  as well as from the opening inspection after Factory Acceptance Test carried out on remaining engines of the same project Fincantieri 6275, which confirmed a satisfactory cleanliness level, Wärtsilä considers the minor impurity noticed in the top of cooling water space of cylinder liner A2 of the engine in object as an accidental event. 
As additional corrective action, cooling water filters of test cell TA3 were inspected and the cooling water charge was totally renewed. 
Before reassembling the relevant cylinder head, the top of cylinder liner A2 was manually cleaned by a cloth soaked with solvent. 
Wärtsilä confirms that the engine in subject can be used without any restriction for its safe and sound operation

ISSUES: Air vent not correctly routed to water expansion tank (no continuous slope). Wärtsilä to explain why this is not a problem for degasing of the engine on test bench whereas there is an issue in the yard on this point.
MeasureTaken:
It is recommended to lead the vent lines separately to the expansion tank. As different parts in the engine have different cooling water pressure levels, there is a risk, with combined vent lines, that some of the vent lines may be blocked due to the pressure difference between the lines and air is not evacuated correctly. Separate venting lines also allow for easier troubleshooting in case of venting issues. 
Conditions during FAT in test cells are not comparable to those of the engines installed in engine room. Test cells at Wartsila premises are designed for maximum flexibility to allow the testing of different engines and configurations. Each test cell has its own water circuit and the time the engine spends in the cell is limited to running-in and FAT period, therefore it is difficult that big amounts of air can accumulate in the circuit.

ISSUES: Rubber in the cylinder head  #1 (channel of water). To be explained.
MeasureTaken:
The rubber element was removed, see picture attached.
The rubber external element found on cylinder head #1 was collected and inspected. The rubber material type and shape was compared with all the components assembled on the engine without finding any correspondence.
Two quality walks were performed in the cylinder head pressure test / pre-assembly department and in test run without finding any correspondence with this material type and shape.
Wartsila classified this rubber deposit as an accidental single case of environmental deposit due to origin of material and quality walks performed. The engine’s parameter related to water circuit fulfil Wartsila standards  and Factory Acceptance Test was performed with satisfactory result.

ISSUES: For some of the cylinders, temperature of liners are very close to the alarm setpoint and are in general higher than on 8L engines. In tropical conditions and with higher LT inlet temperature, this could cause some trouble in operation.
MeasureTaken: Liner temperature is within Wartsila expected values and previous recorded FATs. Furthermore, it depends more on HT temperature rather than ambient air temperature; HT temperature is actively controlled (STX request) and depends on sea water temperature; therefore we do not expect to have limitation on this aspect when operating at tropical conditions. Tropical conditions test has been simulated on PAAE299769 (DG3) with satisfactory results.

ISSUES: High value at low load: 0.37 at 10% and 0.31 at 25% to be compared with 0.2. Not in compliance with technical specifications.
MeasureTaken: Due to operational flexibility needs, test cell exhaust stack in TA3 has several pipe bends and wide diameters; therefore it is not possible to obtain a clean flow for reliable sampling, especially at low load. We are confident that, once on board, where a long straight pipe for sampling is available, FSN will stay within the required values. As proof of this also in previous engines we found similar differences values.

- Temperatures before and after TC: less than 2K increase

ISSUES: Fuel oil consumption to be updated using values from the analysis of fuel sample taken during FAT.
InternalNotes:
Rispondere inviando le analisi dei campioni del Fuel e il valore aggiornato con le analisi dello SFOC all'85%. 
Anche per i motori precedenti
MeasureTaken:
The LHV used for FAT (41,000 MJ/kg) and the LHV of fuel sample analysis (41,000 MJ/kg) is the same. No need to recalculate consumption value (br) at 85% load.
See document: HFO_30_10_2018_TA3.pdf

To explain better different set-up on fuel oil temperatures, as requested:
The difference in the fuel oil temperature recorded on 8L and 12V during FAT, is due to the lower viscosity of the fuel at the moment of the FAT (confirmed by analysis). The heating system is tuned in order to have the correct viscosity on the engine inlet for this reason:
-	In the 8L the fuel oil inlet temp. was slightly higher due to the higher viscosity of the fuel at the moment of the FAT 
-	In the 12V FAT the viscosity was slightly lower due to the lower viscosity at the moment of the FAT  

The two test cell have different heating system and this could have an influence considering also the tolerances.

ISSUES: Fuel oil consumption to be updated using values from the analysis of fuel sample taken during FAT.
InternalNotes:
Rispondere inviando le analisi dei campioni del Fuel e il valore aggiornato con le analisi dello SFOC all'85%. 
Anche per i motori precedenti
MeasureTaken:
The LHV used for FAT (41,000 MJ/kg) is confirm by fuel sample analysis (41,010 MJ/kg). The recalculated consumption value (br) at 85% load is: 182,5 g/kWh (the value in the Test Protocol is: 182,4 g/kWh).
See document: HFO_08_11_2018_TA2.pdf

To explain better different set-up on fuel oil temperatures, as requested:
The difference in the fuel oil temperature recorded on 8L and 12V during FAT, is due to the lower viscosity of the fuel at the moment of the FAT (confirmed by analysis). The heating system is tuned in order to have the correct viscosity on the engine inlet for this reason:
-	In the 8L the fuel oil inlet temp. was slightly higher due to the higher viscosity of the fuel at the moment of the FAT 
-	In the 12V FAT the viscosity was slightly lower due to the lower viscosity at the moment of the FAT  

The two test cell have different heating system and this could have an influence considering also the tolerances.

ISSUES: Fuel oil consumption to be updated using values from the analysis of fuel sample taken during FAT.
InternalNotes:
Rispondere inviando le analisi dei campioni del Fuel e il valore aggiornato con le analisi dello SFOC all'85%. 
Anche per i motori precedenti
MeasureTaken:
The LHV used for FAT (41,000 MJ/kg) is confirm by fuel sample analysis (41,020 MJ/kg). The recalculated consumption value (br) at 85% load is: 181,8 g/kWh (the value in the Test Protocol is: 181,7 g/kWh).
See document: HFO_13_11_2018_TA3.pdf

To explain better different set-up on fuel oil temperatures, as requested:
The difference in the fuel oil temperature recorded on 8L and 12V during FAT, is due to the lower viscosity of the fuel at the moment of the FAT (confirmed by analysis). The heating system is tuned in order to have the correct viscosity on the engine inlet for this reason:
-	In the 8L the fuel oil inlet temp. was slightly higher due to the higher viscosity of the fuel at the moment of the FAT 
-	In the 12V FAT the viscosity was slightly lower due to the lower viscosity at the moment of the FAT  

The two test cell have different heating system and this could have an influence considering also the tolerances.

ISSUES: Slight sign noted on camshaft  of cylinder  B2-B3-B4-B5.. After polishing was found in satisfactory condition. Please give an explanation.
MeasureTaken: The light signs on camshafts were due to some small particles between camshaft and tappet roller working surface during assembly operation (before running test of engine). The lights signs have been easily removed by  hand polishing with soft emery sponge. Camshafts inspected after polishing and found in satisfactory condition.

ISSUES: Brown smoke trace observed on the turbocharger module nearby the exhaust gate valve. To clarify the root cause.
InternalNotes: Da Pulire in finishing, fornire risposta per la causa
MeasureTaken: Discoloration/signs are due to the smoke that come out form insulation covers in the first hours of engine running as consequence of heat up of anti-seize compound on exhaust gas manifold bolts.

ISSUES: Turbocharger suction filters have been polluted by exhaust gas leakages after a few running hours.
MeasureTaken: The exhaust gas system of test bed has to be very flexible to fit wide range of engine sizes and very frequent mounting and dismonting operation. Filter installed on TCs are used only during the FAT.

ISSUES: During the visual inspection, a small plugged hole has been noted (bank A free end). Functionality of plugged hole to be explained.
MeasureTaken: That hole is indispensable for the correct machining of the block Engine. This is the oil channel for the lubrication of the camshaft and then, in the upper part is sealed with an expander (plug).

ISSUES:
A higher fuel consumption ( within contractual value) has been recorder on engine no 3  compare to previous engine. FSN numbers, and exhaust gas temperature deviation compared to the previously tested engines has been detected as well. Owner and Wartsila agreed to proceed with following additional inspections and results will be reported to the all attending parties:

•	Fuel injection pump timing
•	Fuel rack adjustment for each injection pump
•	Valve clearances
•	Injector testing (to be done upon availability of test equipment)

Other possibilities will be evaluated by Wärtsilä if all of the above mentioned  parameters are found to be within tolerances and comparable with previous engine.
Also possible effect of fuel heat value will be considered as based on actual fuel analyses (fuel oil has been bunkered since testing of the previous engine (XAAA847367).
MeasureTaken:
Agreed mechanical check on engine XAAA847371 agreed after FAT have been carried out by Wartsila. The following values have been measured:
-	SOI: All cylinders within tolerance. Average value 7.9 ° bTD, nominal 8° +0/-0.5°OK
Cyl. (SOI)	1 (7,8)	2(8)	3(7.8)	4(8)	5(7.9)	6(7.8)	7(7.8)	8(7.9)	9(7.7)
-	Fuel rack position: only cylinder 8-6-7 had 0.5-1mm more than others. No influence on the SFOC but only on the exhaust temperatures deviation (within tolerance) between cylinders.
-	Valve clearance: found only exhaust valve on cylinder n.7 out of recommendation (plus than 1mm). Valves clearance has been calibrated.
Engine will be delivered in acceptable conditions.

ISSUES: To be check VIC alarm during switch on/off on CV381.
InternalNotes: Fornire una risposta a riguardo (come già fatto per una commessa 46F).
MeasureTaken:
The notification on LDU screen about CV381 / 391 is not a proper alarm.
In order to implement the Load reduction High for CV381 / 391, two logical block have been implemented inside Software.
-	The first logical block “Delayed VIC off ” detects when the VIC command is deactivated (with a delay of 9sec)
-	The second block performs the real Load Reduction  using the first block as input:
 
When the first logical block is set to “1”, on the LDU screen a notification is displayed even if No Action are performed.

ISSUES: Indagare sulla possibilità di integrare in futuro la lettura del datamatrix dei componenti come valvole o seggi anche su Qbase o in ogni caso evitare di dover fare la triscrizione dei codici due volte
CAUSES:
quanto discusso lunedì 18/3/2019nel Alessio Posa meeting:
A seguito dell’aggiornamento dei i piani di controllo qualità Cylinder Head ove vengono richiesti i controlli sulla tracciabilità dei materiali (vedi moduli allegati) si è deciso che il metodista del reparto CH  aggiornerà  entro questa settimana ( week 11) il sistema QBASE per permettere agli operatori di eseguire correttamente  la tracciabilità delle testate cilindro.
Si è condiviso che gli operatori eseguiranno l’appending dei materiali tracciati nei diversi step di montaggio :
1.	Pressatura teste:
•	montaggio seggi scarico 
2.	Montaggio modulo CCH01 :
•	Montaggio valvole di scarico e aspirazione 
•	Montaggio lance (CH W50)

Ove non presenti i datamatrix sui materiali sopra citati gli operatori dovranno trascrivere il seriale number del componente nel QBASE.

Per il controllo del corretto montaggio dei materiali tracciati nei diversi step di assemblaggio è stata introdotta una nuova funzione nel lettore Motorola che permetterà all’operatore di verificare che l’appeding dei materiali previsti siano stati montati correttamnete in tracciabilità, altrimenti dovrà rieseguire l’operazione di appendig al fine di garantire la tracciabilità dei componenti tracciati.
SOLUTIONS: Appena aggiornato il sistema QBASE da parte del metodista , verrà organizzata una dimostrazione / Fast training in reparto per illustrare la nuova funzione di controllo del lettore.

OK a stk Conf in consegna 17/4 trasp rapido Cermesoni 
Il codice paaf324229 (guide block) è arrivato in Wartsila con difetti di verniciatura e porosità (aperto claim al formitore)
8pcs sono stati riparati da metrial mangement e sono tornati in carico al'inspection incoming material. Al momento non possiamo prelevarli in sap perchè si trovano in blocked stock.
CAUSES:
La gestione della pianificazione delle attività di controllo viene influenzata da fattori che interferiscono con le priorità di produzione Es. i ritardi nella consegna di materiali dal fornitore a WIT genera un collo di bottiglia nel controllo in ingresso.
La presenza di componenti di prima fornitura genera ulteriori colli di bottiglia. in ogni caso consgena confermata in sped 17/4 per i PAAF324229 da Besfond e 18/4 da impro in DCT dopo dogana ( nota Gambar 12/4) 
Componenti che rientrano dopo la riparazione confluiscono sempre nello stesso dipartimento generando un altro collo di bottiglia.
SOLUTIONS:
Snellire processo di controllo dei componenti che rientrano in fabbrica dopo la riparazione. possibilmente fare il controllo (es.visual check) direttamente in linea di montaggio, quando necessario a causa della priorità di consegna.

Nel caso di materiali da riparare verificare(prima di rispedirli dal fornitore) che possano essere riparati in loco oppure da subfornitori locali. Verificare gli agreement con i fornitori, soprattutto la tempistica di riparazione riportata nel contratto: non possiamo aspettare che il fornitore impieghi 1 settimana per ripare dei pezzi che ci servono il giorno dopo.

ISSUES:
FC/FAT - R.R. N° OW 4:
Correspondence between fuel timing index on both banks to be checked and corrected (if necessary).
InternalNotes: Verificare regolazione su tutti I motori,. Dare risposta indicando come viene tarata e come funziona in condizione di stop e di funzionamento
MeasureTaken: Timing actuator is calibrated before running in. It is tuned to move exactly from 6mm to 15mm corresponding to the input electrical signal. In case of emergency stop timing rack if forced to move to the lower limit that is below 6 mm. In this case the timing actuator detect a failure in the position and reacts with an alarm. Setscrews are fitted to limit the timing stroke below 6mm and above 15mm. Little deviations can happen due to timing racks clearances.

FC/FAT - R.R. N° OW 4: 
Correspondence between fuel timing index on both banks to be checked and corrected (if necessary).
MeasureTaken: Timing actuator is calibrated before running in. It is tuned to move exactly from 6mm to 15mm corresponding to the input electrical signal. In case of emergency stop timing rack if forced to move to the lower limit that is below 6 mm. In this case the timing actuator detect a failure in the position and reacts with an alarm. Setscrews are fitted to limit the timing stroke below 6mm and above 15mm. Little deviations can happen due to timing racks clearances.
